    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here's a brief summary of the main stages of the US Civil Rights Movement: \n\nThe movement can be divided into five stages: \n\n1. Gandhi-inspired nonviolent resistance (1940s-1950s) led by figures like Roger Baldwin and Mahatma Gandhi.\n2. The Montgomery Bus Boycott (1955-1956) following Rosa Parks' arrest, and the establishment of the Civil Rights Movement.\n3. The Sit-Ins (1960) where students successfully integrated public spaces, sparked by students in Greensboro, North Carolina.\n4. The March on Washington (1963) where Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his famous \"I Have a Dream\" speech.\n5. The Voting Rights Act (1965) and Selma to Montgomery Marches (1965), leading to enforcement of desegregation and voting rights.\n\nThe movement largely achieved major milestones in the law (i.e., Voting Rights Act, desegregation) and social norms (i.e., use of public spaces by minorities), but ongoing struggles remain, marking a limited but significant victory.",
